31
00:02:08,432 --> 00:02:12,332
into the axon and really record the electrical activity

32
00:02:12,588 --> 00:02:16,000
or the voltage difference between the inside and the outside

33
00:02:16,212 --> 00:02:20,675
directly in this giant axon of the squid.

34
00:02:22,942 --> 00:02:25,942
As I said, what Hodgkin and Huxley did

35
00:02:26,143 --> 00:02:32,643
they succeeded to take the squid axon here and put

36
00:02:32,870 --> 00:02:39,383
a wire inside an axon here, so this is this wire I spoke about there,

37
00:02:39,641 --> 00:02:43,254
this is an electrode recording the voltage from within

38
00:02:43,526 --> 00:02:45,601
comparing it to the voltage outside.

39
00:02:45,804 --> 00:02:48,292
So they really measured the voltage drop

40
00:02:48,521 --> 00:02:51,521
the voltage difference between the inside and outside.

41
00:02:51,765 --> 00:02:54,790
Before I defined the membrane voltage

42
00:02:55,009 --> 00:02:55,859
as the difference between

43
00:02:56,047 --> 00:02:58,572
the inside and outside across the membrane

44
00:02:58,784 --> 00:03:02,535
I said that at rest the voltage is -70mV

45
00:03:02,740 --> 00:03:05,340
or something like that, inside versus outside.

46
00:03:05,522 --> 00:03:10,922
But what happens in the squid giant axon?

47
00:03:11,403 --> 00:03:15,353
They used a stimulation, they stimulated the axon

48
00:03:15,537 --> 00:03:18,399
because without stimulation it would sit at rest

49
00:03:18,642 --> 00:03:21,755
something like -70mV at rest,

50
00:03:24,632 --> 00:03:28,145
W=without any perturbation, but now they stimulate here

51
00:03:29,114 --> 00:03:32,952
the axon by making the inside more positive

52
00:03:33,139 --> 00:03:34,026
than it was before.

53
00:03:34,218 --> 00:03:39,143
So instead of -70mV, the move the voltage to -50mV

54
00:03:39,313 --> 00:03:45,338
or -40mV, so the injected current inside of the cell.

55
00:03:46,138 --> 00:03:48,738
And here's what they found.

56
00:03:48,938 --> 00:03:51,250
When you do this you depolarize

57
00:03:51,434 --> 00:03:55,072
we call it depolarize, you make the inside more positive

58
00:03:55,273 --> 00:03:58,760
than the rest, so instead of being -70mV

59
00:03:58,993 --> 00:04:02,755
you depolarize the cell to a given level

60
00:04:03,133 --> 00:04:05,595
and suddenly you get this "boom",

61
00:04:05,771 --> 00:04:08,771
this white signal, the spike

62
00:04:08,969 --> 00:04:11,006
it behaves on its own.

63
00:04:11,226 --> 00:04:13,538
We just brought the membrane to this region

64
00:04:13,729 --> 00:04:16,991
to a given threshold, voltage threshold

65
00:04:17,214 --> 00:04:19,864
and suddenly there's a huge phenomenon

66
00:04:20,079 --> 00:04:24,179
something as I mentioned of the order of 100mV

67
00:04:24,390 --> 00:04:27,640
so it's an all-or-none phenomenon.

68
00:04:28,010 --> 00:04:30,310
It happens or does not happen,

69
00:04:30,549 --> 00:04:33,799
and when it happens it has this very prototypical shape.

70
00:04:34,010 --> 00:04:39,560
A 100mV or so in amplitude about 1ms in duration

71
00:04:39,783 --> 00:04:42,783
and then it's gone.

72
00:04:43,935 --> 00:04:50,422
This was the first inter-cellular direct recording by Hodgkin and Huxley

73
00:04:50,643 --> 00:04:53,643
actually in 1939.

74
00:04:54,588 --> 00:04:57,063
They saw the signal.

75
00:04:57,288 --> 00:04:59,675
But of course seeing the signal on its own

76
00:05:00,011 --> 00:05:04,211
does not mean that you understand the origin, the mechanism

77
00:05:04,454 --> 00:05:06,191
the underlying the signal.

78
00:05:06,408 --> 00:05:09,796
And that's where the genius of Hodgkin and Huxley came

79
00:05:09,987 --> 00:05:12,912
because they systematically analyzed in four papers

80
00:05:13,126 --> 00:05:17,413
actually more, but in 1952, there are four papers, A, B, C

81
00:05:17,608 --> 00:05:23,621
and then the D paper, 1952 D, is the theoretical

82
00:05:23,806 --> 00:05:27,830
the mathematical paper explaining the signal in full.

83
00:05:28,042 --> 00:05:32,867
Very beautifully, very compactly, a very beautiful mathematical model

84
00:05:33,325 --> 00:05:36,075
for understanding the spike.

85
00:05:36,528 --> 00:05:39,353
So, first they showed experimentally that this is indeed

86
00:05:39,564 --> 00:05:42,439
and all-or-none, zero and one

87
00:05:42,628 --> 00:05:43,828
phenomenon.

88
00:05:44,021 --> 00:05:47,308
So look, if they stimulated, if they shift the voltage

89
00:05:47,525 --> 00:05:53,062
from -70mV, which is here, by let's say a few millivolts

90
00:05:53,249 --> 00:05:54,186
let's say, to here

91
00:05:54,378 --> 00:05:57,378
they got some voltage response, which decays.

92
00:06:00,034 --> 00:06:05,196
So this is another attempt, sub-threshold, it decays.

93
00:06:06,374 --> 00:06:09,774
But if you reach enough voltage if you depolarize

94
00:06:10,003 --> 00:06:12,278
if you shift the membrane potential

95
00:06:12,454 --> 00:06:16,542
from -70mV enough, something of the order of 20mV

96
00:06:16,785 --> 00:06:20,698
more positive than -70mV, let's say between -70mV

97
00:06:20,928 --> 00:06:23,653
you shift the voltage by injecting the current

98
00:06:23,843 --> 00:06:26,806
into the cell, positive current inside the cell

99
00:06:27,021 --> 00:06:30,121
then you suddenly see this phenomenon rising.

100
00:06:30,390 --> 00:06:32,440
So this is an action potential.

101
00:06:32,641 --> 00:06:35,866
And if you inject it even stronger, inside the cell

102
00:06:36,050 --> 00:06:38,238
you get another action potential.

103
00:06:38,429 --> 00:06:41,179
But all of this action potential have the same shape

104
00:06:41,397 --> 00:06:43,560
and when they appear, they appear in full.

105
00:06:43,779 --> 00:06:47,179
there is no half-action potential, or a third-action potential.

106
00:06:47,419 --> 00:06:49,756
It's an all or none phenomenon.

107
00:06:49,975 --> 00:06:53,525
So it's either sub-threshold, where you don't get a spike

108
00:06:53,719 --> 00:06:57,319
or it's super-threshold, when you get a full spike.

109
00:06:57,516 --> 00:07:01,554
And again, the threshold is more positive than the resting potential.

110
00:07:01,783 --> 00:07:05,270
So the spike starts from -70mV or -50mV

111
00:07:05,478 --> 00:07:08,228
and then it goes 100mV high and then

112
00:07:08,462 --> 00:07:11,324
it disappears after 1ms, 2ms, or 3ms.

113
00:07:11,536 --> 00:07:16,436
So that's the all-or-none property of the spike.

114
00:07:16,633 --> 00:07:19,371
It's a very interesting signal

115
00:07:19,568 --> 00:07:23,693
as I said, it appears in axons and this was very lucky

116
00:07:23,882 --> 00:07:26,857
for Hodgkin and Huxley to have this squid giant axon

117
00:07:27,053 --> 00:07:29,853
where they could record from the inside and from the outside

118
00:07:30,044 --> 00:07:32,069
and can manipulate ion concentrations

119
00:07:32,256 --> 00:07:33,969
which I'll show you in a second

120
00:07:34,173 --> 00:07:37,173
but they could study the spike directly

121
00:07:37,388 --> 00:07:43,213
in this squid's giant axons and amazingly the same mechanism

122
00:07:43,400 --> 00:07:46,513
of spike generation in axon of the squid giant axon

123
00:07:46,755 --> 00:07:50,705
is also true from most of the axons we know today.

124
00:07:50,891 --> 00:07:53,891
So this basic mechanism that Hodgkin and Huxley found

125
00:07:54,156 --> 00:07:56,844
is really universal for axons of many types

126
00:07:57,104 --> 00:08:00,667
including the axons of the different cell types in our brain

127
00:08:00,858 --> 00:08:07,021
that also generate what we call today a sodium spike.

128
00:08:07,209 --> 00:08:09,934
I will tell you in a second why it's a sodium spike.

129
00:08:10,138 --> 00:08:14,800
Okay, so we came to the point where we now want to go into

130
00:08:15,026 --> 00:08:16,326
the Hodgkin and Huxley model.

131
00:08:16,516 --> 00:08:18,954
So before I just show you the description of the spike

132
00:08:19,181 --> 00:08:22,181
how does it look like, it appears, it disappears

133
00:08:22,393 --> 00:08:26,568
it has a threshold, it is an all-or-none phenomenon.

134
00:08:26,797 --> 00:08:31,384
But now how do you measure the underlying membrane mechanism

135
00:08:31,578 --> 00:08:36,316
that enabled the spikes to be generated?

136
00:08:37,130 --> 00:08:41,693
So that's the beautiful trick that Hodgkin and Huxley were using.

137
00:08:42,553 --> 00:08:46,877
They did actually use two tricks, one is called the Voltage clamp

138
00:08:47,250 --> 00:08:48,188
here

139
00:08:48,646 --> 00:08:50,908
and the other one is called the space clamp.

140
00:08:51,122 --> 00:08:55,072
So their idea was to take this wire, a long wire

141
00:08:55,339 --> 00:08:58,339
into the axon and so the axon becomes

142
00:08:58,987 --> 00:09:03,812
iso-potential, because of this wire which is highly conductive

143
00:09:04,007 --> 00:09:05,882
there is no voltage drop between this location

144
00:09:06,066 --> 00:09:07,065
and this location

145
00:09:07,267 --> 00:09:12,142
so the whole elongated axon becomes electrically very compact

146
00:09:12,350 --> 00:09:15,350
because of this axial wire

147
00:09:15,835 --> 00:09:19,335
but also they use a voltage clamp and that's the ingenious trick

148
00:09:19,530 --> 00:09:22,530
that was not actually only devised by them

149
00:09:22,856 --> 00:09:26,744
but also by others, and the idea was to

150
00:09:26,971 --> 00:09:32,446
try to clamp, to determine the voltage between the two

151
00:09:32,655 --> 00:09:33,718
sides of the membrane,

152
00:09:33,907 --> 00:09:36,219
to force the two sides of the membrane

153
00:09:36,413 --> 00:09:39,538
to have a fixed voltage: a voltage clamp.

154
00:09:40,017 --> 00:09:41,604
Why did they want to do it?

155
00:09:41,801 --> 00:09:44,951
Because they want to measure what currents flow through

156
00:09:45,162 --> 00:09:48,950
the membrane when I clamp the membrane to a given voltage

157
00:09:49,161 --> 00:09:53,149
let's say, now I depolarize the membrane by 20mV

158
00:09:53,353 --> 00:09:56,590
from -70mV to -50mV, and fix it like this.

159
00:09:56,869 --> 00:09:59,119
And then measure which are the currents that flow

160
00:09:59,298 --> 00:10:02,961
through the membrane when I depolarize the membrane by 20mV

161
00:10:03,223 --> 00:10:05,748
30mV, 40mV, and so forth.

162
00:10:05,952 --> 00:10:09,277
So I don't allow the spike to occur anymore

163
00:10:09,503 --> 00:10:11,702
because I've fixed via voltage clamp

164
00:10:11,881 --> 00:10:14,519
the membrane voltage between the two sides

165
00:10:14,722 --> 00:10:17,234
of the membrane, I don't allow it to change

166
00:10:17,460 --> 00:10:20,197
and in order to do it, I need to develop a whole

167
00:10:20,414 --> 00:10:25,689
feedback system, so whenever the spike,

168
00:10:25,901 --> 00:10:29,688
wants to start to be initiated, I block it, I do no allow it

169
00:10:29,914 --> 00:10:33,439
because I want to fix the voltage by injecting a negative current

170
00:10:33,643 --> 00:10:38,518
into the membrane to really balance the voltage into my

171
00:10:38,723 --> 00:10:41,861
voltage clamp pre-determined value.

172
00:10:42,369 --> 00:10:44,607
So I control the spike, so to speak

173
00:10:44,823 --> 00:10:48,223
by fixing the voltage between the two sides of the membrane

174
00:10:48,549 --> 00:10:52,461
by injecting negative currents through my feedback system.

175
00:10:52,722 --> 00:10:57,347
And then I can really measure what current I should inject

176
00:10:57,545 --> 00:11:01,207
in order to fix the voltage between the two sides of the membrane

177
00:11:01,392 --> 00:11:02,579
to be fixed.

178
00:11:02,831 --> 00:11:05,031
And that's the voltage clamp idea.

179
00:11:05,224 --> 00:11:10,574
It enables to uncover the ion currents that flow behind

180
00:11:10,795 --> 00:11:14,082
below the spike, so to speak.

181
00:11:15,004 --> 00:11:18,004
So I've explained to you what is the space clamp

182
00:11:18,218 --> 00:11:21,218
and I've explained to you what is the voltage clamp

183
00:11:22,125 --> 00:11:25,962
and I've told you that this electric feedback system

184
00:11:26,320 --> 00:11:30,082
enables to control the voltage very rapidly

185
00:11:30,277 --> 00:11:33,277
so the voltage between the two sides of the membrane will be fixed.

186
00:11:33,496 --> 00:11:36,308
What did they find using this technique?

187
00:11:36,604 --> 00:11:38,666
So here's what they found:

188
00:11:38,873 --> 00:11:41,585
They found that, when you voltage clamp the membrane

189
00:11:43,501 --> 00:11:47,501
above a certain level, so here they started at -60mV

190
00:11:47,743 --> 00:11:52,993
and they jump to 0mV so this is a 60mV depolarization

191
00:11:53,179 --> 00:11:57,867
and using their feedback system record which are the underlying

192
00:11:58,078 --> 00:12:03,566
currents during this voltage step, voltage clamp,

193
00:12:03,768 --> 00:12:05,517
they see something interesting.

194
00:12:05,712 --> 00:12:11,862
There is a very fast early inward current

195
00:12:12,072 --> 00:12:17,872
and a late outward current.

196
00:12:20,076 --> 00:12:22,951
So they fixed the voltage, they don't change it anymore

197
00:12:23,205 --> 00:12:25,254
so it's a fixed voltage clamp

198
00:12:25,459 --> 00:12:28,221
and they measure the current that needs to be injected

199
00:12:28,449 --> 00:12:31,449
in order to keep the voltage clamp fixed

200
00:12:31,717 --> 00:12:36,330
and they see that in the membrane, while doing this voltage clamp

201
00:12:36,542 --> 00:12:41,979
there is first an inward current, and when I say inward I mean

202
00:12:42,206 --> 00:12:46,631
flowing form the outside into the inside of the cell,

203
00:12:46,874 --> 00:12:50,862
later they found out that this is carried by

204
00:12:51,087 --> 00:12:55,024
sodium channels and if you wait enough time

205
00:12:55,313 --> 00:12:58,226
the current, instead of flowing into the membrane

206
00:12:58,464 --> 00:13:02,914
into the cell, it flows outside and this is the outward current

207
00:13:03,111 --> 00:13:06,111
which is carried by potassium channels

208
00:13:06,492 --> 00:13:08,504
or potassium current.

209
00:13:08,732 --> 00:13:14,445
So this was a very interesting finding that during voltage clamp

210
00:13:14,730 --> 00:13:18,805
and later of course I will show that it's also during the spike itself

211
00:13:19,014 --> 00:13:21,264
when you reach the threshold

212
00:13:21,468 --> 00:13:24,218
very early on, after you reach the threshold

213
00:13:24,427 --> 00:13:28,602
there is an opening of sodium ion channels

214
00:13:28,800 --> 00:13:33,600
that are open because you reach a voltage threshold

215
00:13:33,802 --> 00:13:37,115
so these ion channels are voltage dependent ion channels

216
00:13:37,302 --> 00:13:38,952
we'll talk about this in a second

217
00:13:39,144 --> 00:13:41,032
because you reach this voltage threshold

218
00:13:41,214 --> 00:13:44,614
very early on, there is an inward current

219
00:13:44,816 --> 00:13:49,766
of sodium flowing from the outside to the inside, making the inside

220
00:13:49,982 --> 00:13:53,582
even more positive during the spike

221
00:13:53,804 --> 00:13:56,804
and a little bit later on, a few milliseconds later on

222
00:13:56,996 --> 00:14:01,808
you see an outward current, meaning that the potassium channels

223
00:14:01,992 --> 00:14:07,129
are open carrying current from inside to outside.

224
00:14:08,364 --> 00:14:09,577
Ok?

225
00:14:09,819 --> 00:14:12,319
So there are these two separate currents

226
00:14:12,602 --> 00:14:16,502
that underlay voltage change in the giant squid axon.

227
00:14:16,704 --> 00:14:20,542
The early current which starts and then then ends

228
00:14:20,731 --> 00:14:23,355
so it activates and inactivates

229
00:14:23,631 --> 00:14:26,631
it activates and then inactivates

230
00:14:26,943 --> 00:14:30,806
very fast and early, and then later on there is

231
00:14:31,018 --> 00:14:34,643
a current that is activated, the potassium current is activated

232
00:14:34,829 --> 00:14:38,592
and it lasts as long as there is a voltage clamp.

233
00:14:38,795 --> 00:14:40,270
So we call the early current

234
00:14:40,463 --> 00:14:42,475
we know now that the early current is

235
00:14:42,663 --> 00:14:47,538
sodium-transient activated and inactivated

236
00:14:47,738 --> 00:14:50,163
during the voltage clamp, and the later current

237
00:14:50,374 --> 00:14:53,374
that activates later and remains open

238
00:14:54,032 --> 00:14:57,032
remains flowing this potassium current

239
00:14:57,351 --> 00:15:02,089
remains flowing from inside to the outside of the membrane

240
00:15:02,452 --> 00:15:03,740
during the voltage clamp.

241
00:15:03,930 --> 00:15:07,905
So these are the two basic currents that Hodgkin and Huxley found

242
00:15:08,153 --> 00:15:12,128
that underlie the generation of the spike

243
00:15:12,389 --> 00:15:14,702
in the membrane of the squid giant axon.

244
00:15:14,917 --> 00:15:16,441
What did they do next?

245
00:15:16,633 --> 00:15:17,907
What did they do next?

246
00:15:18,089 --> 00:15:21,976
Next they did voltage clamp to different levels.

247
00:15:22,335 --> 00:15:27,660
Here is an example of voltage clamps to different levels.

248
00:15:28,119 --> 00:15:34,331
So from -60 to -40 from -60 to -20, and so forth

249
00:15:34,575 --> 00:15:37,175
so they clamped the membrane to different levels

250
00:15:37,368 --> 00:15:40,206
and they measured these two currents that I've mentioned before.

251
00:15:40,471 --> 00:15:42,358
The early sodium current

252
00:15:42,543 --> 00:15:46,930
now reversed just for the purpose of showing it

253
00:15:47,134 --> 00:15:50,572
but it should have been inward, it should've been in this direction

254
