equations for the alphas and the betas

516
00:31:21,976 --> 00:31:23,826
for each one of them separately

517
00:31:24,086 --> 00:31:25,774
using all of these four equations

518
00:31:25,973 --> 00:31:28,247
plus the equations for alpha and beta

519
00:31:28,493 --> 00:31:32,831
in a rather old primitive computer, compared to what we have today,

520
00:31:33,099 --> 00:31:37,549
they succeeded to get the full action potential.

521
00:31:38,329 --> 00:31:41,329
Here's the first time you see a simulated

522
00:31:41,706 --> 00:31:42,968
action potential.

523
00:31:43,185 --> 00:31:47,260
So this is the voltage, the solution for this equation

524
00:31:47,430 --> 00:31:48,930
that I showed you before

525
00:31:49,106 --> 00:31:51,243
is the solution for the voltage.

526
00:31:51,706 --> 00:31:55,068
So here is the voltage solved by the Hodgkin and Huxley equation

527
00:31:55,370 --> 00:31:58,070
and you see that the voltage behaves very similarly

528
00:31:58,292 --> 00:31:59,729
to an action potential.

529
00:31:59,947 --> 00:32:04,784
It grows and then it goes down

530
00:32:05,013 --> 00:32:09,463
even bellow the resting potential, and then it terminates.

531
00:32:11,034 --> 00:32:13,810
But of course they could also see the underlying mechanism

532
00:32:14,048 --> 00:32:15,423
because they had a model, for example

533
00:32:15,652 --> 00:32:18,652
you can see that the conductance of the sodium

534
00:32:18,879 --> 00:32:21,879
is the early conductance is the one that initiates

535
00:32:22,225 --> 00:32:23,387
the action potential.

536
00:32:23,640 --> 00:32:24,427
Why?

537
00:32:24,627 --> 00:32:29,002
Because very early on when the action potential starts growing

538
00:32:29,196 --> 00:32:32,196
if you depolarize the membrane enough

539
00:32:32,341 --> 00:32:36,703
this depolarization very early on opens sodium channels

540
00:32:36,883 --> 00:32:39,883
sodium starts flowing into the cell

541
00:32:40,086 --> 00:32:42,424
and then charges the inside of the cell with

542
00:32:42,633 --> 00:32:47,383
positive charge, so the inside of the cell becomes more positive

543
00:32:47,598 --> 00:32:50,173
and then more sodium channels are open

544
00:32:50,397 --> 00:32:53,972
more sodium channels are now carrying sodium charge

545
00:32:54,203 --> 00:32:55,015
into the cell

546
00:32:55,229 --> 00:32:58,504
and the cell becomes more and more positive inside

547
00:32:58,719 --> 00:33:01,719
and this is the blowing of the spike.

548
00:33:03,088 --> 00:33:07,726
But later on, the potassium channels start to open and

549
00:33:07,973 --> 00:33:10,973
potassium channels are later, but they start to open

550
00:33:11,355 --> 00:33:15,992
this now means that the potassium escapes from inside to the outside

551
00:33:16,232 --> 00:33:19,932
due to this gradience potassium leaves the inside of the cell

552
00:33:20,161 --> 00:33:23,436
the potassium ion channels, and this makes the inside

553
00:33:23,640 --> 00:33:28,252
more negative, more negative meaning that you end the action potential

554
00:33:28,455 --> 00:33:30,905
and here even more negative because here there is a lot of

555
00:33:31,155 --> 00:33:36,030
conductance for potassium here and the sodium almost ended

556
00:33:36,244 --> 00:33:40,757
so now the potassium carries membrane potential bellow rest

557
00:33:40,954 --> 00:33:43,954
towards the Nernst battery of the potassium

558
00:33:44,167 --> 00:33:47,167
and then potassium closes a little bit slowly

559
00:33:47,381 --> 00:33:50,269
and then ends the complete phenomenon.

560
00:33:50,513 --> 00:33:53,613
So you'll now realize that the action potential

561
00:33:53,806 --> 00:33:57,693
which actually looks very similar to the biological action potential

562
00:33:57,880 --> 00:34:03,530
by Hodgkin and Huxley equations, is a really good description

563
00:34:03,791 --> 00:34:06,428
of the biological phenomenon that we call spike

564
00:34:06,634 --> 00:34:08,496
or action potential.

565
00:34:08,683 --> 00:34:10,620
So, let me summarize this part.

566
00:34:10,838 --> 00:34:11,988
So as I sad, the Hodgkin and Huxley

567
00:34:12,188 --> 00:34:14,850
is really a marvelous success

568
00:34:15,127 --> 00:34:17,689
of taking biological measurements,

569
00:34:17,964 --> 00:34:20,126
many years of biological measurements

570
00:34:20,318 --> 00:34:21,880
of what ions are involved involved

571
00:34:22,122 --> 00:34:24,734
changing the concentration in sodium and potassium,

572
00:34:24,925 --> 00:34:26,625
but eventually coming to an equation,

573
00:34:26,839 --> 00:34:28,301
a set of four equations,

574
00:34:28,498 --> 00:34:32,873
with some extra equation to describe the rate constance, Alpha and Beta,

575
00:34:33,102 --> 00:34:35,815
and then you get a wonderful description

576
00:34:36,058 --> 00:34:39,333
of this phenomenon that is called the spike.

577
00:34:39,512 --> 00:34:42,337
We know that the spike is carried by two ions,

578
00:34:42,539 --> 00:34:45,453
two main ions potassium and sodium

579
00:34:45,882 --> 00:34:48,882
and that's the main thing

580
00:34:49,104 --> 00:34:54,004
depend on voltage, so these two ions, the capability of two ions

581
00:34:54,224 --> 00:34:57,224
to flow through the membrane, depends on particular channels

582
00:34:57,426 --> 00:34:59,451
in the membrane.

583
00:34:59,661 --> 00:35:01,811
Hodgkin and Huxley used to call them gates

584
00:35:02,047 --> 00:35:05,047
these are gates that are opening and closing the membrane

585
00:35:05,418 --> 00:35:09,480
and these gates are themselves voltage dependent.

586
00:35:09,665 --> 00:35:11,928
So you have a phenomenon that is a voltage phenomenon

587
00:35:12,130 --> 00:35:15,430
the spike, but the voltage of the spike itself

588
00:35:15,651 --> 00:35:18,188
open the channels, first early channels

589
00:35:18,384 --> 00:35:21,046
the sodium channels, which make the spike itself

590
00:35:21,289 --> 00:35:23,901
grow because the spike in the beginning

591
00:35:24,107 --> 00:35:27,332
insert more and more sodium channels into the axon

592
00:35:27,566 --> 00:35:29,391
and more and more of these sodium channels

593
00:35:29,600 --> 00:35:31,825
make the inside more and more positive

594
00:35:32,013 --> 00:35:35,013
until it blows regeneratively, we call it

595
00:35:35,208 --> 00:35:38,608
but then later on the potassium comes in

596
00:35:39,003 --> 00:35:42,915
and the voltage opens the potassium channels

597
00:35:43,120 --> 00:35:44,107
in the membrane.

598
00:35:44,286 --> 00:35:47,698
These potassium channels enable potassium to flow

599
00:35:47,896 --> 00:35:51,083
from the inside to the outside, leaving negative traces inside

600
00:35:51,633 --> 00:35:54,345
and these negative traces inside make

601
00:35:54,565 --> 00:35:57,565
the spike go off,

602
00:35:57,960 --> 00:36:00,397
shut off, turn off.

603
00:36:00,600 --> 00:36:04,299
So this interplay between the fast inward

604
00:36:04,540 --> 00:36:09,515
inactivating  sodium, and the late outward

605
00:36:09,750 --> 00:36:14,063
activated potassium is really the underlying mechanism

606
00:36:14,255 --> 00:36:17,555
of this fantastic phenomenon, the spike.

607
00:36:17,778 --> 00:36:20,991
So the capability of spike to occur in the axon

608
00:36:21,178 --> 00:36:25,016
critically and totally depend on the existence of

609
00:36:25,234 --> 00:36:28,234
specific ion channels in the axons

610
00:36:28,469 --> 00:36:31,469
that are themselves sensitive to voltage.

611
00:36:31,751 --> 00:36:35,076
They are voltage dependent, or what we call "excitable channels"

612
00:36:35,284 --> 00:36:37,771
and this excitability of the channels

613
00:36:37,953 --> 00:36:42,216
enables the spikes to regenerate itself

614
00:36:42,413 --> 00:36:47,376
and blow itself up and then close itself due to the potassium.

615
00:36:48,085 --> 00:36:50,235
So that's what I wanted to say about

616
00:36:50,423 --> 00:36:52,361
the Hodgkin and Huxley equations.

617
00:36:52,586 --> 00:36:56,261
Now, of course, we have fast computers which I hope you will use

618
00:36:56,453 --> 00:36:59,416
your own computer can simulate the Hodgkin and Huxley equation

619
00:36:59,589 --> 00:37:03,264
very fast, Hodgkin and Huxley worked very hard to solve

620
00:37:03,448 --> 00:37:07,748
the equation numerically, but they eventually succeeded

621
00:37:07,968 --> 00:37:12,918
and they got something very nice comparable to what they measured

622
00:37:13,115 --> 00:37:13,940
experimentally.

623
00:37:14,133 --> 00:37:18,071
Before ending this part, I want to say two things.

624
00:37:19,197 --> 00:37:23,072
First of all, as I said

625
00:37:23,254 --> 00:37:26,192
when solving the four equations Hodgkin and Huxley succeeded

626
00:37:26,396 --> 00:37:29,146
to replicate the experimental spike

627
00:37:29,323 --> 00:37:31,685
but not only replicate, and that's a very important

628
00:37:31,866 --> 00:37:35,403
point that I want to make here about a good model.

629
00:37:35,605 --> 00:37:39,943
A good model is not only a replica, of what you already put inside.

630
00:37:40,124 --> 00:37:43,374
A good model, which is very useful for biologists, for example

631
00:37:43,605 --> 00:37:46,305
is a model that gives prediction.

632
00:37:46,496 --> 00:37:49,796
And one of the main predictions of Hodgkin and Huxley is that

633
00:37:49,985 --> 00:37:52,923
after the spike, following the spike

634
00:37:53,134 --> 00:37:56,134
there is a period where you cannot get a second spike.

635
00:37:56,376 --> 00:37:58,638
It's called a refractory period.

636
00:37:58,890 --> 00:38:03,277
This was not a part of the initial model but it was explained

637
00:38:03,472 --> 00:38:06,209
by the Hodgkin and Huxley model, so it's a prediction

638
00:38:06,399 --> 00:38:09,212
by a Hodgkin and Huxley model, we know experimentally

639
00:38:09,405 --> 00:38:12,655
that when you stimulate the axon and very early on

640
00:38:12,860 --> 00:38:16,772
you stimulate again another axon, it won't generate a second spike.

641
00:38:16,984 --> 00:38:20,671
So there is a period, whereby we cannot get a second spike.

642
00:38:20,879 --> 00:38:23,254
It's a very important period, the refractory period

643
00:38:23,440 --> 00:38:25,590
because it sets the frequency of spikes

644
00:38:25,774 --> 00:38:27,836
that the axon can generate.

645
00:38:28,047 --> 00:38:30,347
One spike, and then stop, no spike,

646
00:38:30,526 --> 00:38:31,951
no matter what you do

647
00:38:32,189 --> 00:38:33,426
and then a second spike.

648
00:38:33,653 --> 00:38:36,653
It's called the refractory period, let's say every 10ms

649
00:38:36,873 --> 00:38:38,798
you can get a spike, this means

650
00:38:38,993 --> 00:38:42,318
hundred spikes per second, hundred hertz.

651
00:38:43,149 --> 00:38:46,149
So the Hodgkin and Huxley model prejudiced and explained

652
00:38:46,481 --> 00:38:49,106
the phenomenon of the refractory period.

653
00:38:49,280 --> 00:38:54,967
In the same 1952-D paper also predicted the velocity of

654
00:38:55,209 --> 00:38:59,521
the spike, which is not a part of this local model.

655
00:38:59,740 --> 00:39:03,077
The velocity of the spike depends on the length of the axon

656
00:39:03,292 --> 00:39:04,617
the width of the axon

657
00:39:04,823 --> 00:39:06,860
they predicted the velocity of the spike

658
00:39:07,077 --> 00:39:10,702
in the squid giant axon, in their mathematical equation

659
00:39:10,886 --> 00:39:12,323
and it was really, indeed

660
00:39:12,511 --> 00:39:14,461
the same velocity measured experimentally.

661
00:39:14,677 --> 00:39:17,902
So this is a very powerful model because it doesn't only replicate

662
00:39:18,122 --> 00:39:21,497
the experimental result, but it explained other results

663
00:39:21,688 --> 00:39:24,688
that were not part of the original model.

664
00:39:25,160 --> 00:39:27,247
And finally, I want to say something very important

665
00:39:27,464 --> 00:39:30,852
which I already highlighted or mentioned before

666
00:39:31,096 --> 00:39:34,096
is that the Hodgkin and Huxley model is a universal model

667
00:39:34,395 --> 00:39:37,395
in the sense that, no matter what cell you take

668
00:39:37,786 --> 00:39:40,724
let's say, now I take for you this cell, which is

669
00:39:40,923 --> 00:39:46,610
a pyramidal cell reconstructed from the cortex, actually

670
00:39:46,813 --> 00:39:51,950
human cell, human pyramidal cell, you saw before, and this is the axon

671
00:39:52,155 --> 00:39:56,518
of this human pyramidal cell, or this is a piece of an axon

672
00:39:57,242 --> 00:39:59,417
And you can see that, if you measure

673
00:39:59,622 --> 00:40:02,622
in this particular cell

674
00:40:05,771 --> 00:40:07,821
if you measure in this particular cell

675
00:40:08,026 --> 00:40:10,776
the spiking activity, you get the spikes.

676
00:40:11,033 --> 00:40:14,033
These are the experimental spikes, these are the brown spikes.

677
00:40:14,260 --> 00:40:17,697
One spike, another spike, another spike.

678
00:40:17,908 --> 00:40:20,908
These are the experimental spikes.

679
00:40:21,141 --> 00:40:23,403
But now if you model the spikes using

680
00:40:23,593 --> 00:40:26,081
the extension of Hodgkin and Huxley and when I say

681
00:40:26,277 --> 00:40:31,127
extension of Hodgkin and Huxley, I mean that the same formalism

682
00:40:31,349 --> 00:40:33,012
exactly the same formalism

683
00:40:33,201 --> 00:40:36,063
but adding additional currents

684
00:40:36,346 --> 00:40:39,346
still carried by sodium, potassium, or calcium

685
00:40:39,956 --> 00:40:42,856
but with different kinetics, so different Alphas

686
00:40:43,038 --> 00:40:46,501
and different Betas for different channels, we know that there are

687
00:40:46,727 --> 00:40:49,452
slow potassium channels, even slower then in

688
00:40:49,634 --> 00:40:51,247
in the Hodgkin and Huxley case

689
00:40:51,465 --> 00:40:53,477
there are ion channels in the membrane

690
00:40:53,674 --> 00:40:57,974
that are sensitive to calcium, so the channels not only depend on

691
00:40:58,161 --> 00:41:00,698
voltage but also on calcium, and so forth,

692
00:41:00,921 --> 00:41:03,921
but it's the same formalism, and when you extend

693
00:41:03,971 --> 00:41:06,971
the Hodgkin and Huxley formalism, you can get the firing patterns

694
00:41:07,247 --> 00:41:09,935
essentially of every cell in the brain.

695
00:41:10,113 --> 00:41:13,625
This is just one example, the green model

696
00:41:13,845 --> 00:41:17,082
succeeds to replicate the firing of this particular cell

697
00:41:17,276 --> 00:41:19,263
which is a cortical cell, nothing to do with

698
00:41:19,475 --> 00:41:22,188
the squid giant axon, but still fires spikes

699
00:41:22,376 --> 00:41:25,638
and spikes and spikes, but the pattern of activity

700
00:41:25,833 --> 00:41:27,521
depends on these extra channels,

701
00:41:27,775 --> 00:41:30,125
not only the generation of the single spike

702
00:41:30,343 --> 00:41:33,393
but when will the next spike arrive, and the next spike arrive

703
00:41:33,615 --> 00:41:36,090
depends on these other channels with the same

704
00:41:36,256 --> 00:41:37,356
Hodgkin and Huxley formalism.

705
00:41:37,555 --> 00:41:40,280
So it's a wonderful model because it not only captures

706
00:41:40,470 --> 00:41:44,495
the spike in the squid giant axon, it captured the whole universal

707
00:41:44,704 --> 00:41:47,179
phenomenon of a spike in any cell

708
00:41:47,403 --> 00:41:49,415
and that's why we, in many ways

709
00:41:49,625 --> 00:41:52,825
really adore Hodgkin and Huxley, because they gave us the tool

710
00:41:53,051 --> 00:41:58,813
to simulate one of the two most important signals in the brain,

711
00:41:59,001 --> 00:42:02,001
electrical signals : the spike.

